In this R practice, I will use stock price data from the past 5 years to construct a Relative Stength Index.

The RSI is a momentum indicator that is used in technical analysis to:

  • measure the speed and magnitude of a securitys recent price changes.

  • evaluate undervalued and overvalued conditions in security price.

The RSI indicates securities primed for trend reversals and collective price pullbacks.

It signals to traders when to buy and when to sell.

  • RSI > 70: the stock is overbought (overvalued).

  • RSI < 30: the stock is oversold (undervalued).

It compares the strength of securities on days when prices go up to the strength on days when they go down.

\[ RSI_{stepone}= 100 - [\frac{100}{1+\frac{avg. gain}{avg. loss}}] \]

\[ RSI_{steptwo} = 100 - [\frac{100}{1 + \frac{(Pvt. Avg. Gain * 13)+current gain} {(Pvt. Avg. Loss * 13) + current loss}}] \] Installing the libraries that will allow me to download the data.

Programming the RSI function.

  • First, I will program RSI functions for each of the six stocks which I have.

  • Step 1 : add columns containing the RSI for each of the six stocks next to their adjusted closing price.

  • Step 2: Create diagrams with the stock price graph above and the RSI graph below for each of the six stocks chosen for this analysis.

myRSI <- function (price,n){
  N <- length(price)
  U <- rep(0,N)
  D <- rep(0,N)
  rsi <- rep(NA,N)
  Lprice <- Lag(price,1)
  for (i in 2:N){
    if (price[i]>=Lprice[i]){
      U[i] <- 1
    } else {
      D[i] <- 1
    }
    if (i>n){
      AvgUp <- mean(U[(i-n+1):i])
      AvgDn <- mean(D[(i-n+1):i])
      rsi[i] <- AvgUp/(AvgUp+AvgDn)*100 
      }
    }
  rsi <- reclass(rsi, price)
  return(rsi)
}


rsi_meta <- myRSI(stocks$Meta, n = 14)
rsi_amzn <-myRSI(stocks$Amazon, n =14)
rsi_aapl <- myRSI(stocks$Apple, n = 14)
rsi_nflx <- myRSI (stocks$Netflix, n = 14)
rsi_goog <- myRSI (stocks$Alphabet, n =14)
rsi_msft <- myRSI (stocks$Microsoft, n = 14)

Adding the 6 RSI XTS objects to the stocks XTS object and dsiplaying descriptive statistics about the RSIs

stocks.f <- merge (stocks, rsi_meta, rsi_amzn, rsi_aapl, rsi_nflx, rsi_goog, rsi_msft)
